designing oceanic fiber optic cables, and I lived in Africa for several years.

20
00:02:12,065 --> 00:02:14,869
So, in the Nemesis system, what we like to do...

21
00:02:18,381 --> 00:02:21,504
is we like to surprise and delight the player

22
00:02:21,624 --> 00:02:23,605
and evoke these emotions of love and hate.

23
00:02:23,926 --> 00:02:25,607
So this talk is gonna be about that.

24
00:02:25,647 --> 00:02:27,529
We're gonna get into the nemesis system.

25
00:02:28,149 --> 00:02:30,491
We're going to talk about how we do this,

26
00:02:30,691 --> 00:02:33,814
why we wanna do it, talk about some philosophies

27
00:02:33,894 --> 00:02:36,756
of our design and some tricks and a lot of examples.

28
00:02:37,897 --> 00:02:39,919
And here's the summary in case you gotta go.

29
00:02:42,000 --> 00:02:45,222
The players hate it when you inhibit their progress and insult them.

30
00:02:45,662 --> 00:02:47,703
And they love it if you help them and entertain them.

31
00:02:48,123 --> 00:02:53,026
And it really helps to have a long relationship, as long as possible.

32
00:02:53,286 --> 00:02:59,170
And it helps to be a memorable orc, to be a nemesis, not only in who they are but what they do.

33
00:03:00,800 --> 00:03:02,460
So what is the Nemesis system?

34
00:03:03,480 --> 00:03:06,221
Well, a short answer could be it is procedural bosses.

35
00:03:06,741 --> 00:03:08,241
I like this longer answer better.

36
00:03:08,341 --> 00:03:10,062
It's an interconnected game mechanics

37
00:03:10,202 --> 00:03:14,583
that allow players to develop Nemesis-style relationships

38
00:03:14,663 --> 00:03:16,443
with systemically generated enemies

39
00:03:16,923 --> 00:03:18,704
using systemically generated events.

40
00:03:19,104 --> 00:03:21,444
And when I say Nemesis-style relationships,

41
00:03:21,724 --> 00:03:24,885
what I mean is that classic relationship

42
00:03:24,925 --> 00:03:28,646
that is long-term, that you see between two main characters

43
00:03:28,926 --> 00:03:30,527
over time where there's respect.

44
00:03:31,127 --> 00:03:32,850
and fear of each other.

45
00:03:32,950 --> 00:03:34,793
So there's a lot of examples of these.

46
00:03:34,873 --> 00:03:36,797
Here's a few that you probably know.

47
00:03:36,857 --> 00:03:39,000
This is Sherlock Holmes and Moriarty,

48
00:03:39,040 --> 00:03:41,224
and this is Beowulf and Grendel.

49
00:03:42,397 --> 00:03:45,858
So the Nemesis system isn't what it's all about.

50
00:03:45,878 --> 00:03:47,139
It's only a part of the game.

51
00:03:47,179 --> 00:03:50,321
There's a huge set of game mechanics and systems

52
00:03:50,461 --> 00:03:55,363
that exist that only, Nemesis system can only be enjoyed

53
00:03:55,443 --> 00:03:57,765
and even perceived if these other things are in place

54
00:03:57,825 --> 00:03:58,465
and are awesome.

55
00:03:59,345 --> 00:04:00,706
And it isn't a separate thing either.

56
00:04:00,906 --> 00:04:02,067
It is deeply integrated.

57
00:04:02,087 --> 00:04:03,728
It's got its roots in everything.

58
00:04:03,768 --> 00:04:06,369
The whole team helps to bring that whole thing to life.

59
00:04:07,955 --> 00:04:09,715
And the nemesis system can be thought of,

60
00:04:10,395 --> 00:04:12,316
interesting stories, and interesting stories

61
00:04:12,376 --> 00:04:16,597
can only exist on top of a sense of normalcy.

62
00:04:17,797 --> 00:04:18,917
Once you establish normalcy,

63
00:04:18,937 --> 00:04:20,478
you can have the interesting things happen

64
00:04:20,498 --> 00:04:23,618
because only when things stand out as interesting,

65
00:04:23,638 --> 00:04:25,219
then people say, oh yeah,

66
00:04:25,439 --> 00:04:26,819
it's different than everything else I've seen.

67
00:04:27,900 --> 00:04:30,480
So the best example of gameplay.

68
00:04:31,820 --> 00:04:34,121
for the Nemesis system is the revenge loop.

69
00:04:34,421 --> 00:04:38,503
And in the revenge loop, it follows these steps.

70
00:04:39,263 --> 00:04:42,105
The orc kills you, then you respawn,

71
00:04:42,785 --> 00:04:46,086
and this is important, time moves forward in our game,

72
00:04:46,786 --> 00:04:50,028
which means you don't go back to where you were alive,

73
00:04:50,508 --> 00:04:53,749
you wake up later, then you decide to hunt down the orc,

74
00:04:54,930 --> 00:04:56,210
and then you kill the orc.

75
00:04:58,567 --> 00:05:00,748
This is different than what players want.

76
00:05:01,068 --> 00:05:02,368
Of course, they want to kill every orc

77
00:05:02,428 --> 00:05:03,448
and they want to never die.

78
00:05:03,988 --> 00:05:06,569
And when this is deviated from their expectations

79
00:05:07,149 --> 00:05:08,549
is when it starts to get really interesting.

80
00:05:09,189 --> 00:05:11,490
So I have a video of this revenge loop.

81
00:05:11,730 --> 00:05:12,550
I'm gonna show you now.

82
00:05:12,910 --> 00:05:14,910
And I spliced it and I sped up some parts

83
00:05:15,030 --> 00:05:17,211
so that we can get to the really interesting parts

84
00:05:17,271 --> 00:05:18,051
and I highlighted them.

85
00:05:18,391 --> 00:05:19,091
So let's take a look.

86
00:05:19,751 --> 00:05:21,911
Ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha!

87
00:05:21,951 --> 00:05:25,792
Submit now, and perhaps I will show you a bit of mercy.

88
00:05:42,110 --> 00:05:49,194
Nothing personal. I'm just following orders from my overlord. He says kill the Tark. I kill the Tark

89
00:05:50,115 --> 00:05:54,537
Actually was a little personal because I really do hate Tarks

90
00:06:03,863 --> 00:06:05,123
So here time was forward

91
00:06:10,653 --> 00:06:12,534
Now I'm trying to find the orc again.

92
00:06:53,141 --> 00:06:55,462
All right, let's talk about when time moves forward.

93
00:06:55,782 --> 00:06:57,163
In a lot of single-player games,

94
00:06:58,003 --> 00:06:59,864
you actually have the option to,

95
00:06:59,984 --> 00:07:02,245
or you're forced to even, go back in time.

96
00:07:02,985 --> 00:07:06,566
And what that means is it's part of your thought process.

97
00:07:07,127 --> 00:07:09,848
So pardon my crude designer drawings,

98
00:07:10,268 --> 00:07:12,169
but here's me playing the game,

99
00:07:12,209 --> 00:07:14,710
and I'm thinking to myself, oh, this is a hard part.

100
00:07:14,730 --> 00:07:15,550
Should I save?

101
00:07:15,710 --> 00:07:17,131
Maybe I'll reload.

102
00:07:18,331 --> 00:07:20,394
Maybe I'll reload version A or version B.

103
00:07:20,834 --> 00:07:24,618
Now I'm actually in my own gameplay process.

104
00:07:24,779 --> 00:07:27,782
I'm like watching myself in my little time travel experiment.

105
00:07:28,243 --> 00:07:31,446
I think I'll reload B if I fail here, otherwise A might be good.

106
00:07:32,791 --> 00:07:36,793
In our game, we are forced to move forward in time.

107
00:07:36,833 --> 00:07:38,314
You don't have the option to go back,

108
00:07:38,674 --> 00:07:40,055
and it's freeing in a way.

109
00:07:40,595 --> 00:07:43,677
It helps you focus on what's happening immediately.

110
00:07:44,077 --> 00:07:46,058
You don't have to play that little experiment

111
00:07:46,098 --> 00:07:48,639
because all you're focused on is what's gonna happen next,

112
00:07:49,240 --> 00:07:51,181
what just happened, and you end up being

113
00:07:51,381 --> 00:07:55,163
very emotionally involved with the immediate events

114
00:07:55,183 --> 00:07:55,783
that are happening.

115
00:07:56,304 --> 00:07:58,765
And the bonus is you have a longer relationship

116
00:07:58,805 --> 00:08:00,626
with the orcs, because now they have a memory

117
00:08:00,646 --> 00:08:01,247
that they can hold.

118
00:08:02,427 --> 00:08:06,696
So in the revenge loop, here are the emotions that go through the typical player.

119
00:08:07,529 --> 00:08:10,011
like, oh, I'm so frustrated, I just died.

120
00:08:10,111 --> 00:08:13,353
And then most people, they abandon whatever they're doing

121
00:08:13,454 --> 00:08:15,955
and they're like, that orc, he's dead, I'm going after him.

122
00:08:16,336 --> 00:08:17,837
Then they hunt him down, they find him,

123
00:08:18,057 --> 00:08:19,118
and then they kill him, and they're like,

124
00:08:19,138 --> 00:08:21,119
oh, this is so amazing, that felt good.

125
00:08:21,940 --> 00:08:23,501
And I liken it to a roller coaster,

126
00:08:23,541 --> 00:08:27,064
so like, oh, I hated that part, oh, here we go, yeah!

127
00:08:27,344 --> 00:08:28,745
That was a great hill that we went down.

128
00:08:29,225 --> 00:08:31,887
So here's the key is that we like the negative emotions.

129
00:08:31,987 --> 00:08:32,948
We really like it.

130
00:08:33,909 --> 00:08:36,970
because it leads to that glorious result.

131
00:08:37,310 --> 00:08:39,391
In fact, if it's strong negative,

132
00:08:39,731 --> 00:08:41,291
it leads to a stronger positive.

133
00:08:41,572 --> 00:08:43,252
So we want that roller coaster hill

134
00:08:43,292 --> 00:08:44,613
to be higher if possible.

135
00:08:45,353 --> 00:08:48,734
It's also similar to doing hard work.

136
00:08:48,774 --> 00:08:50,355
So here's a fruit tart.

137
00:08:50,395 --> 00:08:53,216
If I make a fruit tart, it's a lot of work to put into it,

138
00:08:53,276 --> 00:08:56,037
but man, after you finish, it tastes way better.

139
00:08:56,057 --> 00:08:56,097
So.

140
00:08:59,751 --> 00:09:02,233
We have support for this, here's a couple.

141
00:09:02,973 --> 00:09:04,094
Georgia R. Martin says,

142
00:09:04,474 --> 00:09:06,976
fiction is about emotional resonance,

143
00:09:07,136 --> 00:09:11,499
about making us feel things on a primal and visceral level.

144
00:09:12,000 --> 00:09:15,782
And so I interpret that as emotions are the whole point.

145
00:09:16,323 --> 00:09:19,665
If you're not gonna do the emotions, why even do it?

146
00:09:21,026 --> 00:09:23,328
So here's an article we got when we released Shadow of War.

147
00:09:25,553 --> 00:09:30,896
So this article, so like, I'm being bullied by Mozu.

148
00:09:30,916 --> 00:09:32,097
That's his voice.

149
00:09:33,278 --> 00:09:33,738
Oh, awesome.

150
00:09:34,058 --> 00:09:34,218
Yeah.

151
00:09:36,340 --> 00:09:36,520
Yeah.

152
00:09:37,761 --> 00:09:37,961
Yeah.

153
00:09:37,981 --> 00:09:38,101
Yeah.

154
00:09:38,121 --> 00:09:38,341
Yeah.

155
00:09:38,741 --> 00:09:40,943
This article is very satisfying to get

156
00:09:40,983 --> 00:09:45,485
because it shows that he's on his way up that rollercoaster

157
00:09:45,506 --> 00:09:47,527
and a few days later he wrote the subsequent one.

158
00:09:47,547 --> 00:09:48,127
Yeah.

159
00:09:48,728 --> 00:09:48,848
Yeah.

160
00:09:48,868 --> 00:09:51,729
And he shows like, yeah, this is, it was proof to us.

161
00:09:51,789 --> 00:09:52,970
This is working like this.

162
00:09:53,370 --> 00:09:54,751
This is really where it's all about.

163
00:09:55,537 --> 00:09:58,038
So this leads me to philosophy number one.

164
00:09:58,999 --> 00:10:00,420
So I have a bunch of philosophies,

165
00:10:00,480 --> 00:10:02,221
and by the way, they're kind of all swirling

166
00:10:02,241 --> 00:10:04,482
and all over the place, so they're not really

167
00:10:04,502 --> 00:10:06,763
part of a list, it's not exhaustive.

168
00:10:07,664 --> 00:10:08,444
I have, I think, seven.

169
00:10:08,985 --> 00:10:10,766
So here's philosophy number one.

170
00:10:11,306 --> 00:10:12,807
We want to maximize the hate, why?

171
00:10:13,087 --> 00:10:15,849
Because the resolution is way more sweeter.

172
00:10:16,975 --> 00:10:17,956
And there's two parts of this.

173
00:10:18,456 --> 00:10:20,218
One of it is that the orcs are mean,

174
00:10:20,418 --> 00:10:23,941
and the other is we want to get you to hate the orc,

175
00:10:24,521 --> 00:10:25,562
not hate the game.

176
00:10:26,923 --> 00:10:28,304
And so let's talk about orcs being mean.

177
00:10:29,507 --> 00:10:33,250
There's a lot of tricks we do, but we basically try to do it everywhere we can.

178
00:10:34,131 --> 00:10:41,817
One example is the kill animations. You saw that example. When that orc kills you, we show those brutal, supposed to look painful.

179
00:10:42,117 --> 00:10:46,881
You know, talion is suffering. And then when he stands over you and talks to you, he insults you.

180
00:10:46,921 --> 00:10:51,325
He says things that are really aggravating, if possible, or memorable.

181
00:10:52,005 --> 00:10:55,968
And then when he's promoted, he's like, yeah, I'm stronger now because of your failure.

182
00:10:56,637 --> 00:11:01,038
And then we also spent a lot of time focusing on the orc's face.

183
00:11:01,658 --> 00:11:04,019
And the next time he meets you, of course, he insults you again.

184
00:11:04,079 --> 00:11:05,199
Why, you died.

185
00:11:05,299 --> 00:11:06,079
I can kill you again.

186
00:11:06,119 --> 00:11:06,720
You're so easy.

187
00:11:08,140 --> 00:11:10,301
So let's talk about the death taunts.

188
00:11:10,641 --> 00:11:13,101
Death taunts is the moment right when you're dying.

189
00:11:13,121 --> 00:11:16,782
And he looks over your dying body, and then he

190
00:11:16,842 --> 00:11:17,803
says something insulting.

191
00:11:18,323 --> 00:11:20,504
I have a little clip showing a few examples

192
00:11:20,964 --> 00:11:24,085
of being insulting and memorable.

193
00:11:30,680 --> 00:11:37,344
If you're the best that men can offer, this war will be disappointingly short.

194
00:11:38,404 --> 00:11:41,886
You wanted to beat me, didn't you?

195
00:11:42,586 --> 00:11:49,911
Must be frustrating losing the way you did. Just makes this all the more fun for me!

196
00:12:10,692 --> 00:12:12,393
Don't promote me for this!

197
00:12:12,714 --> 00:12:14,335
Maybe a few times!

198
00:12:14,675 --> 00:12:17,718
I could be War Chief, I could be Overlord...

199
00:12:18,279 --> 00:12:18,719
I could be...

200
00:12:19,240 --> 00:12:19,360
Ah!

201
00:12:20,000 --> 00:12:20,941
Whatever's above that!

202
00:12:24,525 --> 00:12:27,968
We come to this, your sad little end.

203
00:12:27,988 --> 00:12:33,453
I do like to think we were almost friends.

204
00:12:36,918 --> 00:12:41,941
Okay, we want to get the player to focus their hate on the orc, not the game.

205
00:12:42,201 --> 00:12:46,643
And the key to this is the players have to feel like there was a solution available to them

206
00:12:47,043 --> 00:12:49,745
within their grasp, something they could have done to avoid it.

207
00:12:49,765 --> 00:12:52,646
Oh, if only I... Here's some examples.

208
00:12:52,686 --> 00:12:54,687
If only I won that last chance minigame.

209
00:12:54,987 --> 00:12:58,449
If only I got intel, I would have known he has that special move that killed me.

210
00:12:59,049 --> 00:13:01,790
Oh, I forgot to run away. We can always run away in our game.

211
00:13:02,633 --> 00:13:04,875
So here's a story about this.

212
00:13:05,316 --> 00:13:07,198
During development of Shadow of Mordor,

213
00:13:07,519 --> 00:13:10,362
we were putting in the trait No Chance.

214
00:13:10,422 --> 00:13:12,624
And before we had the banner that

215
00:13:12,644 --> 00:13:15,568
showed across the bottom of the screen, it was partially working.

216
00:13:16,175 --> 00:13:19,396
and it was implemented, we were experiencing it in the game,

217
00:13:19,416 --> 00:13:22,277
Bob Roberts said, oh, this feature is terrible,

218
00:13:22,357 --> 00:13:24,939
it makes me feel terrible, why are we even doing this?

219
00:13:25,059 --> 00:13:26,739
And then the banner finally got in the game,

220
00:13:27,119 --> 00:13:28,620
and he said, oh, yeah, okay, now it's fine,

221
00:13:28,820 --> 00:13:31,481
yeah, it's fine, because it means I could have known,

222
00:13:31,581 --> 00:13:33,262
if I had done research on that orc,

223
00:13:33,302 --> 00:13:35,003
which a lot of times you need to do,

224
00:13:35,823 --> 00:13:37,084
I would have seen it as no chance,

225
00:13:37,124 --> 00:13:40,405
it would have changed the way I approached my behavior,

226
00:13:40,445 --> 00:13:41,306
I could have avoided it.

227
00:13:42,226 --> 00:13:43,046
So let's go back to that,

228
00:13:46,096 --> 00:13:50,060
That loop that I was talking about. So you first meet the captain and he insults you and then

229
00:13:50,080 --> 00:13:54,825
He then you get killed and this is the moment of aggravation

230
00:13:54,865 --> 00:13:58,849
of course the orcs promoted and I want to point out that you don't have to be killed by

231
00:13:59,412 --> 00:14:01,292
a captain, you could be killed by a grunt.

232
00:14:02,252 --> 00:14:04,153
And that's kind of the beauty of our game.

233
00:14:04,273 --> 00:14:05,373
It's not just the captains.

234
00:14:05,573 --> 00:14:08,493
Any grunt who happens to get a lucky shot on you

235
00:14:08,874 --> 00:14:09,454
can kill you.

236
00:14:09,754 --> 00:14:11,154
